  <para>
    Find edges in an &image;.  The <varname>radius</varname> parameter
    sets the size of the convolution filter, in units of the pixel
    size.  Setting it to 0 will cause a suitable value to be chosen
    automatically.
  </para>
  <para>
    This routine comes from the <ulink url="http://www.imagemagick.org"
    role="external">ImageMagick</ulink> library.
  </para>
  <figure id="Figure-EdgeDetect">
    <title>Detecting Edges in an Image</title>
    <mediaobject>
      <imageobject>
	<imagedata fileref="FIGURES/imageops/raw.png" format="PNG"/>
      </imageobject>
      <imageobject>
	<imagedata fileref="FIGURES/imageops/raw.eps" format="EPS"/>
      </imageobject>
      <caption>
	<para>
	  A micrograph of
	  Si<subscript>3</subscript>N<subscript>4</subscript>
	  (courtesy of C.-H. Hsueh).
	</para>
      </caption>
    </mediaobject>
    <mediaobject>
      <imageobject>
	<imagedata fileref="FIGURES/imageops/edge0.png" format="PNG"/>
      </imageobject>
      <imageobject>
	<imagedata fileref="FIGURES/imageops/edge0.eps" format="EPS"/>
      </imageobject>
      <caption>
	<para>
	  The result of applying <command>Edge</command> with
	  <varname>radius</varname>=0
	  (<foreignphrase>i.e,</foreignphrase> automatic radius selection).
	</para>
      </caption>
    </mediaobject>  
    <mediaobject>
      <imageobject>
	<imagedata fileref="FIGURES/imageops/edge1.png" format="PNG"/>
      </imageobject>
      <imageobject>
	<imagedata fileref="FIGURES/imageops/edge1.eps" format="EPS"/>
      </imageobject>
      <caption>
	<para>
	  The result of applying <command>Edge</command> with
	  <varname>radius</varname>=1.
	</para>
      </caption>
    </mediaobject>
  </figure>

